g1': 'European screenwriter brother director wife director'}, 'id': 'call_16efd6102b79496bb5f6e449', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 17074, 'output_tokens': 182, 'total_tokens': 17256, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 145}}), ToolMessage(content='Link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Hill\n\nPage: Walter Hill\nSummary: Walter Hill (born January 10, 1942) is an American filmmaker, known for his action films and revival of the Western genre.\nHe has directed such films as The Driver, The Warriors, Southern Comfort, 48 Hrs. and its sequel Another 48 Hrs., Streets of Fire and Red Heat, and wrote the screenplay for the crime drama The Getaway. He has also directed several episodes of television series such as Tales from the Crypt and Deadwood and produced films in the Alien franchise.\nHe founded Brandywine Productions with David Giler and Gordon Carroll.\nHill said in an interview that "every film I\'ve done has been a Western", and elaborated in another that "the Western is ultimately a stripped down moral universe that is, whatever the dramatic problems are, beyond the normal avenues of social control and social alleviation of the problem, and I like to do that even within contemporary stories".\n\nPage: Luc Besson\nSummary: Luc Paul Maurice Besson (French: [lyk bɛsɔ̃]; born 18 March 1959) is a French filmmaker. He directed and produced the films Subway (1985), The Big Blue (1988), and La Femme Nikita (1990). Associated with the Cinéma du look film movement, he has been nominated for a César Award for Best Director and Best Picture for his films Léon: The Professional (1994) and The Messenger: The Story of Joan of Arc (1999). He won Best Director and Best French Director for his sci-fi action film The Fifth Element (1997). He wrote and directed the sci-fi action film Lucy (2014), the space opera film Valerian and the City of a Thousand Planets (2017), Dogman (2023), and the fantasy romantic movie Dracula (2025).\nIn 1980, near the beginning of his career, he founded his own production company, Les Films du Loup, later renamed Les Films du Dauphin. It was superseded in 2000 when he co-founded EuropaCorp with longtime collaborator Pierre-Ange Le Pogam. As writer, director, or producer, Besson has been involved in the creation of more than 50 films.\n\nPage: Coen brothers\nSummary: Joel Coen and Ethan Coen, known as the Coen brothers (), are an American filmmaking duo. Their films span many genres and styles, which they frequently subvert or parody. Among their most acclaimed works are Blood Simple (1984), Raising Arizona (1987), Miller\'s Crossing (1990), Barton Fink (1991), Fargo (1996), The Big Lebowski (1998), O Brother, Where Art Thou? (2000), No Country for Old Men (2007), A Serious Man (2009), True Grit (2010), and Inside Llewyn Davis (2013).\nThe brothers generally write, direct and produce their films jointly, although due to DGA regulations, Joel received sole directing credit while Ethan received sole production credit until The Ladykillers (2004), from which point on they would be credited together as directors and producers; they also shared editing credits under the alias Roderick Jaynes. The duo started directing separately in the 2020s, beginning with Joel\'s The Tragedy of Macbeth (2021) and Ethan\'s Jerry Lee Lewis: Trouble in Mind (2022) and Drive-Away Dolls (2024). They have been nominated for 13 Academy Awards together, plus one individual nomination for each, sharing wins for Best Original Screenplay for Fargo, and Best Picture, Best Director and Best Adapted Screenplay for No Country for Old Men. Barton Fink won the Palme d\'Or at the 1991 Cannes Film Festival.\nThe Coens have written films for other directors, including Sam Raimi\'s Crimewave (1985), Angelina Jolie\'s World War II biopic Unbroken (2014) and Steven Spielberg\'s Cold War drama Bridge of Spies (2015). They produced Terry Zwigoff\'s Bad Santa (2003) and John Turturro\'s Romance and Cigarettes (2005).  Ethan is also a writer of short stories, theater and poetry.\nNo Country for Old Men, A Serious Man and Inside Llewyn Davis were included on the BBC\'s 2016 poll of the greatest films since 2000. In 1998, the American Film Institute ranked Fargo among the 100 greatest American movies. They are known for their distinctive stylistic trademarks including genre hy\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Hill] ---\nTitle: Walter Hill\n\nURL Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Hill\n\nPublished Time: 2006-04-27T21:50:14Z\n\nMarkdown Content:\n| Walter Hill |\n| --- |\n| [![Image 1](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1e/Walter_Hill_1137_%28cropped%29.jpg/250px-Walter_Hill_1137_%28cropped%29.jpg)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Walter_Hill_1137_(cropped).jpg) Hill in 2014 |\n| Born | January 10, 1942 (age 84) [Long Beach, California](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Beach,_California "Long Beach, California"), U.S. |\n| Education | [Michigan State University](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michigan_State_University "Michigan State University") ([BA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bachelor_of_Arts "Bachelor of Arts")) |\n| Occupations | * Film director * screenwriter * film producer |\n| Years active | 1968–present |\n| Spouse | Hildy Gottlieb \u200b (m.1986)\u200b |\n| Children | 2 |\n\n**Walter Hill** (born January 10, 1942) is an American filmmaker, known for his [action films](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_film "Action film") and revival of the [Western genre](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_(genre) "Western (genre)").[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Hill#cite_note-hill1-1) He has directed such films as _[The Driver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The\\_Driver "The Driver")_, [_The Warriors_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Warriors_(film) "The Warriors (film)"), [_Southern Comfort_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southern_Comfort_(1981_film) "Southern Comfor... [truncated]', name='wikipedia', id='6de1dbb1-9ff8-4a5f-90fc-c100441ddcff', tool_call_id='call_16efd6102b79496bb5f6e449'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 117, 'prompt_tokens': 18677, 'total_tokens': 18794, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 66, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 117}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 18677}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-1ba3d2d7-972a-9c14-80f0-6ce86b1ea23c', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9e8e-f908-7331-bfca-ef99800a0d88-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': '"短篇小说" "双线叙事" 电影 导演 兄弟 欧洲 编剧 2024'}, 'id': 'call_32d3144a451d40bc80f73671', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 18677, 'output_tokens': 117, 'total_tokens': 18794, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 66}}), ToolMessage(content="SYSTEM ALERT: You have used the tool 'common_search' 3 times, which is the limit for a single tool. You MUST switch to a DIFFERENT search tool (e.g., use 'academic_search' or 'web_search' instead of 'common_search'). Using the same tool repeatedly is ineffective. TRY ANOTHER TOOL.", name='common_search', id='6e695638-df0b-4305-b438-949a1d9bcadb', tool_call_id='call_32d3144a451d40bc80f73671'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 187, 'prompt_tokens': 18809, 'total_tokens': 18996, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 146, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 187}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 18809}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-41ff9b87-a652-9886-a8fa-2cccb1a30772', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9e8f-084e-7c70-894a-93adb12e35fe-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'wikipedia', 'args': {'__arg1': 'screenwriter short story brother director film two narrative lines Europe'}, 'id': 'call_59306036fea64adbae283740', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 18809, 'output_tokens': 187, 'total_tokens': 18996, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 146}}), ToolMessage(content='Link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film)\n\nPage: Paris, Texas (film)\nSummary: Paris, Texas is a 1984 neo-Western drama road film directed by Wim Wenders, co-written by Sam Shepard and L. M. Kit Carson, and produced by Don Guest. A co-production of West Germany, France, and the United Kingdom, it stars Harry Dean Stanton, Nastassja Kinski, Dean Stockwell, Aurore Clément, and Hunter Carson. In the film, Travis Henderson (Stanton) reunites with his brother Walt (Stockwell) and son Hunter (Carson) after an unexplained four-year absence. Travis and Hunter embark on a road trip through the American Southwest to track down Hunter’s mother, Jane (Kinski).\nAt the 1984 Cannes Film Festival, the film won the Palme d\'Or from the official jury, as well as the FIPRESCI Prize and the Prize of the Ecumenical Jury. It went on to receive other honors and widespread critical acclaim for its direction, screenplay, acting, cinematography, emotional resonance, and musical score. It has become a cult classic and is widely considered one of the greatest films ever made. It has been called an exemplar of both independent cinema and the road film. In the decennial critics\' poll published by the British Film Institute\'s magazine Sight and Sound in 2022, Paris, Texas placed 185th.\n\nPage: The Day of the Jackal (film)\nSummary: The Day of the Jackal is a 1973 political thriller film directed by Fred Zinnemann and starring Edward Fox and Michael Lonsdale. Based on the 1971 novel by Frederick Forsyth, the film is about a professional assassin known only as the "Jackal" who is hired to assassinate French president Charles de Gaulle in the summer of 1963. It stars Edward Fox as the title character, with Michael Lonsdale, Derek Jacobi, Terence Alexander, Michel Auclair, Alan Badel, Donald Sinden, Tony Britton, Cyril Cusack, Maurice Denham and Delphine Seyrig. The musical score was composed by Georges Delerue.\nA co-production of the United Kingdom and France, The Day of the Jackal received positive reviews and went on to win the BAFTA Award for Best Editing (Ralph Kemplen), five additional nominations (including Best Film and Best Direction), two Golden Globe Award nominations, and one Oscar nomination. The film grossed $16,056,255 at the North American box office, returning $8,525,000 in rentals to the studio. In 1999, the British Film Institute ranked it the 74th greatest British film of the 20th century.\nA remake of the film was released in 1997. A TV adaptation of the novel and film aired on Sky Atlantic in 2024.\n\n\n\nPage: Joseph L. Mankiewicz\nSummary: Joseph Leo Mankiewicz ( MANG-kə-wits; February 11, 1909 – February 5, 1993) was an American filmmaker. A four-time Academy Award winner, he is best known for his witty and literate dialogue and his preference for voice-over narration and narrative flashbacks. Also known as an actor\'s director, Mankiewicz directed several prominent actors, including Bette Davis, Gene Tierney, Humphrey Bogart and Elizabeth Taylor, to several of their memorable onscreen performances. \nBorn in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania, Mankiewicz studied at Columbia University and graduated in 1928. He moved overseas to Europe, where he worked as a foreign correspondent for the Chicago Tribune and translated German intertitles into English for UFA. On the advice of his screenwriter brother Herman, Mankiewicz moved back to the United States, and was hired by Paramount Pictures as a dialogue writer. He then became a screenwriter, writing for numerous films starring Jack Oakie. He next moved to Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer (MGM), where he served as a producer for several films, including The Philadelphia Story (1940) and Woman of the Year (1942). Mankiewicz left MGM after a dispute with Louis B. Mayer.\nIn 1944, Mankiewicz began working for Twentieth Century-Fox, where he produced The Keys of the Kingdom (1944). He made his directorial debut with Dragonwyck (1946) after Ernst Lubitsch had dropped out due to illness. Mankiewicz remained at Twentieth Century-Fox, directing a broad range of genre films. C\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film] ---\nTitle: The Day of the Jackal (film - Wikipedia\n\nURL Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film\n\nWarning: Target URL returned error 404: Not Found\n\nMarkdown Content:\nPage contents not supported in other languages.\n\n*   [Article](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film&action=edit&redlink=1 "View the content page (page does not exist) [alt-c]")\n*   [Talk](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Talk:The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film&action=edit&redlink=1 "Discuss improvements to the content page (page does not exist) [alt-t]")\n\nTools\n\nActions\n\nGeneral\n\n*   [What links here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:WhatLinksHere/The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film "List of all English Wikipedia pages containing links to this page [alt-j]")\n*   [Upload file](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:File_Upload_Wizard "Upload files [alt-u]")\n*   Printable version\n*   [Page information](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Day_of_the_Jackal_(film&action=info "More information about this page")\n*   [Get shortened URL](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.p